article.headline: Minnesota wins despite 30 from Storm's Jackson
article.linkText: Smith saves Lynx down the stretch
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Playing short-handed was no problem for the
Lynx.

Katie Smith scored 19 points, and Sherri Sam added 16 and a
career-high eight assists as Minnesota beat the Seattle Storm 69-58
on Sunday.

Playing without second-leading scorer Svetlana Abrosimova
(strained hamstring) and backup point guard Kristi Harrower
(tonsils), Minnesota reached beyond its usual seven-player
rotation.

Sam and center Michele Van Gorp picked up the slack. The duo
combined for 29 points on 11 of 17 shooting and eight rebounds.

"We were missing two key people," Sam said. "We all had to
have energy and bounce back after our Cleveland loss (last
Thursday). We needed everybody."

Lynx coach Suzie McConnell Serio said Harrower is likely to play
on Wednesday at Connecticut, while Abrosimova remains questionable.

This game had the makings of a blowout. A spinning layup at the
buzzer by Minnesota's Teresa Edwards cut Seattle's lead to 34-33 at
halftime. Then the Lynx (11-9) went on an 18-8 spurt and sprinted
out to a 51-38 lead on Smith's three-pointer eight minutes into the
second half.

But then nobody could stop Seattle's Lauren Jackson, who had a
career-high 30 points in 28 minutes. Minnesota's Jannell Burse and
Jordan Adams came off the bench and racked up six fouls in 11
minutes trying to stop the 6-foot-5 center.

Jackson scored 18 of the Storm's next 20 points, the last of
which pulled Seattle (11-9) to within 59-58 with 3:38 left.

"It was encouraging to come back, but we just didn't get over
that line," she said. "We didn't win, so it wasn't that
encouraging."

Standing around during most of Seattle's run, the Lynx watched
another big lead fizzle away.

"I looked at my assistants and said, 'Why can't we play with a
13-point lead?" McConnell Serio said.

But Minnesota found a second wind on Smith's three-pointer and a
tough floater in the lane to push the lead back to 64-58 with 2 1/2
minutes remaining, and Seattle was not heard from again.

Besides Jackson, the Storm combined to shoot 11 of 43 (26
percent) for the game. No one else finished in double figures.

The Storm played all but three minutes of the game without
injured point guard Sue Bird (knee), who averages 13.4 points per
game and a league-best 7.2 assists per game.

The Lynx have won four of their last five games and moved into a
third-place tie with Seattle in the Western Conference standings.
After winning in Seattle last month, Minnesota is assured of at
least a split in the teams' four-game series this season.

"I don't think this was important in the sense of playoff
contention," Jackson said. "We've still got a lot of games left.
It was no big deal ... just another game."
